body:

---

### Purpose

`AccessorFunction` is of type `(row: object) => any`. This pull request has the purpose to type this depending on the given data `D[]`, so that `(row: D) => any` is the type.


### Further information 

The pull request removes `object` as a potential argument.

https://github.com/andys8/DefinitelyTyped/blob/52de94b301c4b5b4a8289690e13fe180f659ce7c/types/react-table/index.d.ts#L10

Since a `function` is also an `object` this would match wrong functions. It could be possible to use [conditional types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/release-notes/typescript-2-8.html) and exclude this case. I tried so, but I wasn't able to use it the intended way with typescript. The [documentation](https://react-table.js.org/#/story/readme) has not a lot of information, but as of now I think that there is no valid way to pass an `object` in typescript. Therefore I think it's better to remove this case.

body:
Hi, `@types/jest-axe` maintainers (@JoshuaKGoldberg)!

I'm currently running into an issue in #29753 where the build is failing because of this error (which I'm also getting locally):

```

=== ERRORS ===
Error in jest-axe
Error: /home/travis/build/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/types/jest-axe/node_modules/axe-core/axe.d.ts:23:24
ERROR: 23:24  expect  TypeScript@next compile error: 
Cannot find name 'Node'.

    at Generator.next (<anonymous>)
    at fulfilled (/home/travis/build/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/node_modules/dtslint/bin/index.js:5:58)

Error: The following packages had errors: jest-axe
    at runTests (/home/travis/build/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/node_modules/types-publisher/src/tester/test-runner.ts:126:8)
    at <anonymous>
    at process._tickCallback (internal/process/next_tick.js:189:7)
```

It looks like `axe-core` is a dependency of `@types/jest-axe`, and the declaration file for `axe-code`[ is referencing `Node`](https://github.com/dequelabs/axe-core/blob/f98b83085afb79d5327ea73b0f40ac2c9e346cc1/axe.d.ts#L23
), which is available via the "dom" library. By making this change, I was able to fix issue and the tests for my other PR are passing.


Please let me know if this makes sense to you. I'm also curious to know why this wasn't an issue before .

title: [gltf] Add typings for glTF 2.0
body:
Adds typings for glTF 2.0, a file format for 3D assets.

/cc @bghgary Could you confirm this still works as expected in BabylonJS? I made a couple (hopefully minor) changes:

1. Added typings for `bufferView.target`
2. Replaced all enums with a type and a namespace, like:

```typescript
/**
 * Interpolation algorithm
 */
export type AnimationSamplerInterpolation = "LINEAR" | "STEP" | "CUBICSPLINE";
export namespace AnimationSamplerInterpolation {
    /**
     * The animated values are linearly interpolated between keyframes
     */
    const LINEAR = "LINEAR";
    /**
     * The animated values remain constant to the output of the first keyframe, until the next keyframe
     */
    const STEP = "STEP";
    /**
     * The animation's interpolation is computed using a cubic spline with specified tangents
     */
    const CUBICSPLINE = "CUBICSPLINE";
}
```

The step above is redundant, but without that a glTF object does not validate correctly, because enum strings are opaque. See: https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/issues/17690.

Also note the "definitions by" header  we'll automatically be pinged if someone opens a PR on these typings. Should anyone else be listed?
